<Docs
  title="What's inside"
  eyebrow="Documentation · Reference"
  summary="Every tool, default, and system change the bootstrap makes, and why it's there."
>
  <p>
    Nothing here is a surprise. This page is the complete inventory — if the
    bootstrap touches it, it's listed below.
  </p>

  <h2 id="shell">bash</h2>
  <p>
    The interactive shell gets safety rails and a handful of aliases that pay
    for themselves daily. Destructive commands prompt before they act:
  </p>
  <Code caption="dotfiles/bash/aliases.sh">
    <span class="tok-comment"># guard against fat-fingered destruction</span>
    alias rm=<span class="tok-flag">'rm -I'</span>
    alias cp=<span class="tok-flag">'cp -i'</span>
    alias mv=<span class="tok-flag">'mv -i'</span>

    <span class="tok-comment"># commit + push in one move: gp "message" branch</span>
    gp() {'{'} git add . && git commit -m <span class="tok-flag">"$1"</span> && git push origin <span class="tok-flag">"$2"</span>; {'}'}
  </Code>
  <ul>
    <li><code>ll</code>, <code>la</code>, <code>l</code> — the usual <code>ls</code> shorthands, with colour.</li>
    <li><code>gp "msg" branch</code> — stage, commit, and push in one command.</li>
    <li>History that ignores duplicates and appends across sessions.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="herdr">herdr</h2>
  <p>
    <a href="https://herdr.dev">herdr</a> is the terminal multiplexer — a
    keyboard-driven, agent-aware replacement for tmux. It's a single Rust
    binary with <strong>no account and no telemetry</strong>, which is exactly
    why it's here. The prefix is <code>C-a</code>, panes navigate like vim, and
    it ships beautiful themes:
  </p>
  <Code caption="dotfiles/herdr/config.toml — highlights">
    [keys]
    prefix = <span class="tok-flag">"ctrl+a"</span>          <span class="tok-comment"># screen-style prefix</span>
    focus_pane_left = <span class="tok-flag">"prefix+h"</span> <span class="tok-comment"># vim pane navigation</span>
    split_vertical = <span class="tok-flag">"prefix+v"</span>

    [update]
    version_check = false        <span class="tok-comment"># privacy: no update pings</span>

    [theme]
    name = <span class="tok-flag">"vesper"</span>
    auto_switch = true           <span class="tok-comment"># light by day, dark by night</span>
  </Code>
  <p>
    See every option with <code>herdr --default-config</code>. Update on your
    own terms with <code>herdr update</code>.
  </p>

  <h2 id="runtimes">mise</h2>
  <p>
    Language runtimes are managed by <a href="https://mise.jdx.dev">mise</a> —
    one tool for node, ruby, and python, with per-project versions pinned in a
    <code>.mise.toml</code>. No more juggling nvm, rbenv, and pyenv.
  </p>
  <Code>
    <span class="tok-prompt">$</span> mise use node@lts    <span class="tok-comment"># pin a runtime for this project</span>
    <span class="tok-prompt">$</span> mise install         <span class="tok-comment"># install everything a repo asks for</span>
  </Code>

  <h2 id="git">git &amp; gh</h2>
  <p>
    Git ships with sensible defaults and uses the
    <a href="https://cli.github.com">GitHub CLI</a> as its credential helper, so
    you authenticate once with <code>gh auth login</code> and never paste a token
    again. Your name and email go in an untracked <code>~/.gitconfig.local</code>.
  </p>

  <h2 id="privacy">Privacy — turning off calls home</h2>
  <p>
    A stock Ubuntu install phones home in several small ways. The
    <code>privacy</code> step turns them off — all reversible:
  </p>
  <Code caption="setup/steps/40-privacy.sh">
    <span class="tok-comment"># remove Canonical metrics and crash reporting</span>
    apt purge ubuntu-report popularity-contest apport whoopsie

    <span class="tok-comment"># stop the login "news" fetch and the NetworkManager ping</span>
    /etc/default/motd-news                 ENABLED=0
    /etc/NetworkManager/conf.d/…           connectivity enabled=false
  </Code>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>ubuntu-report</strong> and <strong>popularity-contest</strong> — usage and package metrics, removed.</li>
    <li><strong>apport</strong> / <strong>whoopsie</strong> — crash reports to Canonical, removed.</li>
    <li><strong>motd-news</strong> — the remote "news" line on login, disabled.</li>
    <li><strong>connectivity check</strong> — NetworkManager's ping to a Canonical endpoint, disabled.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="hardening">Security hardening</h2>
  <p>
    A sensible baseline that won't get in your way. The <code>hardening</code>
    step brings up a firewall, turns on automatic security updates, and applies
    a short list of kernel and network <code>sysctl</code> settings:
  </p>
  <Code caption="setup/steps/50-hardening.sh">
    ufw default deny incoming    <span class="tok-comment"># nothing gets in unless you allow it</span>
    ufw default allow outgoing
    ufw enable

    <span class="tok-comment"># /etc/sysctl.d/90-ubuntu-setup-hardening.conf</span>
    kernel.kptr_restrict = 2     <span class="tok-comment"># hide kernel pointers</span>
    kernel.dmesg_restrict = 1
    net.ipv4.tcp_syncookies = 1
  </Code>
  <p>
    <strong>unattended-upgrades</strong> is enabled so security patches land
    automatically. Nothing here opens a port or exposes a service — it only
    tightens the defaults.
  </p>

  <h2 id="efficiency">Efficiency &amp; battery</h2>
  <p>
    On Ubuntu 26.04 with a kernel 7 base, the <code>power</code> step installs
    a boot-time <a href="https://github.com/fenrus75/powertop">powertop</a>
    auto-tune service so the machine uses the kernel's power-saving paths on
    every boot — real gains in idle battery life:
  </p>
  <Code>
    <span class="tok-comment"># runs once at every boot via a oneshot systemd unit</span>
    /usr/sbin/powertop --auto-tune
  </Code>

  <h2 id="packages">apt packages</h2>
  <p>
    A curated set of command-line tools, installed in one pass. The list lives
    in a plain text file you can edit before running:
  </p>
  <Code caption="setup/packages.txt">
    build-essential    <span class="tok-comment"># compilers and make</span>
    ripgrep fd-find    <span class="tok-comment"># fast search</span>
    jq                 <span class="tok-comment"># JSON on the command line</span>
    ufw                <span class="tok-comment"># firewall</span>
    powertop           <span class="tok-comment"># power tuning</span>
    git curl           <span class="tok-comment"># the essentials</span>
  </Code>
  <p>
    <em>herdr isn't an apt package</em> — it's installed by the
    <code>herdr</code> step from <code>herdr.dev/install.sh</code>.
  </p>

  <h2 id="framework">Framework fixes</h2>
  <p>
    When the bootstrap detects a Framework 13 or 16 mainboard, the
    <code>power</code> step configures the fingerprint reader and points you at
    the deepest suspend state for the best idle battery. On any other hardware
    this part is skipped entirely — it's guarded behind a device check, so the
    repo is safe to run anywhere.
  </p>

  <p>
    For where each of these lives on disk, see
    <a href={href('/docs/layout/')}>Repository layout</a>.
  </p>
</Docs>
